WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:12.960
Hi everyone, I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
Welcome to this lecture on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:19.680
a new way of thinking about arithmetic by using&nbsp;
the idea of a multi-set, this foundational data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:28.140
structure concept to build up the entire theory,&nbsp;
including algebra, in a systematic or step-by-step&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:34.980
fashion, from really the most essential simple&nbsp;
kind of object perhaps that we can imagine, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.980 --> 00:00:42.720
is an empty set or an empty multi-set. So what&nbsp;
we're doing here is trying to expand our point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:50.880
of view from the set-theoretical orientation that&nbsp;
20th-century mathematics largely had, which was,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:55.320
of course, built up from the need of analysts&nbsp;
to have a foundation for their understanding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:01.860
of analysis on the Continuum. So Dedekind's&nbsp;
theory of real numbers required Cantor's theory&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:09.480
of infinite sets, and so the need for infinite&nbsp;
sets became important. And then this 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:17.040
axiomatic approach to set theory was the sort of&nbsp;
philosophical substitute for a proper foundation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:25.920
And since then, more and more mathematicians have&nbsp;
leaned on sets as sort of foundational objects in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:30.480
mathematics and have tried to frame everything,&nbsp;
or largely everything, in terms of sets.

00:01:31.260 --> 00:01:36.660
Now, sets are well and good, but they're really&nbsp;
only one of several possible data structures that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:42.600
are available to us, and in particular, multi-sets&nbsp;
are a very important alternative, and they allow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:47.760
us to see a lot of different things in a very&nbsp;
different light. So today, we're going to see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:51.720
a really good example of that because we're going&nbsp;
to move towards exponentiation. This is the third&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:58.320
of our operations in this world of multi-sets, and&nbsp;
it's quite different from the exponentiation that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:03.660
you're familiar with, so be prepared for some&nbsp;
serious novelty, and we're going to have to go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:08.700
slowly and carefully. I'm going to exhibit lots of&nbsp;
examples so you can see how this actually works,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.700 --> 00:02:12.540
and at the end of the video, you'll see that&nbsp;
there are actually some really remarkable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.540 --> 00:02:17.940
properties that this thing has, so it really&nbsp;
is deserving of our study and our attention.

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:25.380
The basic framework is that we've set up this&nbsp;
idea of inductive or recursive building up of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:31.200
ever more complicated objects, starting with&nbsp;
zero, which is just the empty mset, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:37.740
msets of zero are called natural numbers. Msets&nbsp;
of natural numbers are called poly numbers. Msets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:41.340
of poly numbers are called multi numbers,&nbsp;
and of course, we could carry on like this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:45.600
Today, what we're going to do is we're&nbsp;
going to introduce some parallel things:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:56.820
first of all, some counting functions that&nbsp;
allow us to roughly assign sizes to some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.820 --> 00:03:01.980
of these multi-sets that we're looking at.&nbsp;
So we're going to introduce Z, N, P, and M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:09.900
obviously paralleling these different types. And&nbsp;
so these are going to be counting functions, with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.900 --> 00:03:15.360
N being the one that's most familiar, counting&nbsp;
the number of objects in a set or a collection.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:25.380
And then we're going to look at this hierarchy of&nbsp;
operations that is potentially available to us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:30.480
starting with addition and then multiplication,&nbsp;
and moving crucially today to exponentiation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:35.940
And throughout, I want you to have this idea&nbsp;
that we're looking in this direction, and we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:41.580
can sort of see that the steps that we're taking&nbsp;
can be extended in a very obvious and natural way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:45.540
right? So at all of these points, I want you&nbsp;
to be thinking, "I wonder what happens if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:50.220
we go one step further or two steps further&nbsp;
or something like this?" Things get richer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:54.540
they get more complicated, we get a bigger&nbsp;
picture. So there's a lot of thinking to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:54.540 --> 00:04:01.560
done and try to move in this direction in this&nbsp;
interesting, somewhat new world of mathematics.

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:09.540
Now, before I go on, it's the beginning of&nbsp;
New Year 2023, so happy New Year to everyone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:16.440
and a special thanks to my Patreon supporters&nbsp;
and to members of my Wild Egg Mathematics Courses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:23.760
YouTube channel. You guys are great. Thanks so&nbsp;
much for your support. It's really appreciated.

00:04:24.840 --> 00:04:29.400
All right, so this video will be very much&nbsp;
building on Math Foundations 227 and 228,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:33.120
the two previous ones, so please make sure&nbsp;
you watch them. But a very quick review:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:39.300
so we have these different types. Zero is&nbsp;
just the empty mset, denoted with brackets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:44.160
like this or with the symbol zero. So that's&nbsp;
what zero is in our world. Natural numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:49.380
are msets of zeros. For example, that's an&nbsp;
mset of zeros, and the simplest one is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:49.380 --> 00:04:54.540
mset just consisting of zero. That's going to&nbsp;
be called one. This one here is called four.

00:04:54.540 --> 00:05:00.600
So this is where the usual primary school natural&nbsp;
number arithmetic takes place. Then, one step up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:06.660
msets of natural numbers are called poly&nbsp;
numbers. The simplest one is Alpha zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.380
which is not already a natural&nbsp;
number, and zero is Alpha zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:14.640
which is the mset consisting of&nbsp;
one. Here's a typical poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:20.640
which can then be interpreted as in the form&nbsp;
two plus Alpha zero plus Alpha zero cubed.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:27.420
Then to the next stage, multi numbers are&nbsp;
msets of poly numbers. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:30.540
this thing here, that's a polynomial, that's&nbsp;
a polynomial, that's a polynomial. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:35.280
that's an mset of poly numbers. And then, when&nbsp;
we introduce this new notation, Alpha one for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:40.920
the mset containing Alpha zero, Alpha two&nbsp;
for the mset containing Alpha zero squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.920 --> 00:05:46.200
Alpha three containing Alpha zero cubed,&nbsp;
then we can write something like this as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:52.260
multinomial if you like, involving several&nbsp;
variables. In this case, Alpha zero, Alpha one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.260 --> 00:05:55.800
Alpha two, Alpha four, and in principle,&nbsp;
we could have more and more variables.

00:05:57.060 --> 00:06:03.600
Then, addition is the sort of fundamental object.&nbsp;
If you have an mset here, another mset here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:10.140
the way you add them is you just dump&nbsp;
the contents out into another box. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:15.240
this mc01, this number three, this&nbsp;
mc2 get moved in the other box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.240 --> 00:06:17.760
and the two elements here, one&nbsp;
and four, get moved in the box.

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:22.440
Multiplication is a little bit more&nbsp;
sophisticated. The way you multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:28.500
two msets is that you add the elements&nbsp;
of this mset with the elements of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:33.360
set in all possible ways and form a&nbsp;
multi-set of all those possible sums.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:38.820
So, this one here has two elements, multi-set&nbsp;
06 and number one. This one also, two elements,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.820 --> 00:06:45.000
number four and multi-set two. When we multiply&nbsp;
them, we have to take the sum of this and this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.920
which is this mset, sum of this and this, which&nbsp;
is this one, sum of this and this, which is this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:54.420
and some of this and this, which is this.&nbsp;
Make sure that you understand those examples.

00:06:55.140 --> 00:07:01.680
So, that's a very quick overview, and now&nbsp;
we want to go further. So, we've informally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:05.520
used the word "element of an mset." Let me be&nbsp;
a little bit more careful about that and also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:11.280
introduce some important notation. So, here's an&nbsp;
example of an mset consisting of zero, zero, one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.280 --> 00:07:18.300
and another mset containing two and three. So,&nbsp;
we'll say that the elements of this mset are zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:18.300 --> 00:07:25.860
zero, one, two, three. So, this is a big box and&nbsp;
inside it has other boxes, and those other boxes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.860 --> 00:07:31.140
very well may have other stuff inside them, okay?&nbsp;
But the boxes that you can see are the elements&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:37.560
of the bigger box, including their contents. So,&nbsp;
we then write, to denote this element relation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:43.680
zero is an element of A, one is an element of A,&nbsp;
and this multi-set two, three is an element of A.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.520 --> 00:07:51.060
So, these are all separate true statements.&nbsp;
And if X is a general mset, then we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:57.600
to introduce this kind of notation to allow us to&nbsp;
describe the elements. So, the brackets mean mset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:01.860
okay, and here is sort of the object that we're&nbsp;
considering or the objects that we're considering,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:07.980
and the colon here represents some condition, and&nbsp;
the condition is that little X belongs to capital&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:13.140
X. In other words, there's an element of capital X&nbsp;
in this set here. So, what we're saying here, this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:18.720
is the way of thinking about X. It's the multi-set&nbsp;
consisting of all X where X is an element of X.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:22.620
So, in this case, we would have&nbsp;
to run through all of these: zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:26.700
zero, one, and two, three, as we are running&nbsp;
through the elements of X. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:33.480
we have to respect the natural multiplicities that&nbsp;
are occurring here throughout. Okay, so it's very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:38.040
different from set theory in that way. There's&nbsp;
two zeros here, we have to keep those two zeros&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:41.220
separate, we have to keep track of&nbsp;
them, there's two of them there.

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:47.940
Let me illustrate the usefulness of this&nbsp;
notation by starting again with this mset A,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.940 --> 00:08:53.100
and here are some other msets defined&nbsp;
in terms of the elements of A. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:59.040
B is the mset of things in the form A&nbsp;
plus one, where A is in capital A. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:03.960
we have to take each one of these elements, and we&nbsp;
have to add one to them. So, zero plus one is one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:08.520
zero plus one is one, one plus one is two, and&nbsp;
if we add one to this, well, remember, one is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:13.740
mset consisting of zero. So, when we add those&nbsp;
two msets, we get the mset zero, two, three.

00:09:13.740 --> 00:09:21.780
Here's mset C, which is the set of two&nbsp;
times A where A is an element of A. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.780 --> 00:09:27.300
we have to multiply each of these things&nbsp;
by two. Okay, so two times zero is zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.300 --> 00:09:31.800
two times zero is zero, two times one is two,&nbsp;
two times this thing is this mset right here.

00:09:33.660 --> 00:09:39.480
Here is a more complicated thing where we're&nbsp;
taking two M sets, say this A and this B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:46.140
and we're actually taking their product,&nbsp;
AB, or we could possibly, more precisely,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.140 --> 00:09:51.840
say A times B. All right, we will sometimes use&nbsp;
this, but actually this is probably preferred,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:57.120
okay? And so, what is the definition of that?&nbsp;
Well, in terms of this notation, it's the set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.120 --> 00:10:03.420
of A plus B such that A belongs to capital A and&nbsp;
B belongs to capital B. So, what we have to do is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:09.660
we have to go through these two sets here and take&nbsp;
sums of things. So, the zero and the one is one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:15.360
the zero and the one is one, the zero and the two&nbsp;
is two, and the zero and plus this is itself. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:19.380
then when we repeat it with this one, we get the&nbsp;
same thing. And then when we add one, we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:24.540
to get two, two, three. And this thing, when&nbsp;
we add two, three to everything, we get two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:33.540
three plus one is this one, two, three plus one&nbsp;
is this one, two, three plus two is this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:39.900
because two is the mset consisting of two zeros.&nbsp;
And finally, when we add this one and this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:47.700
we get this one here. Okay, so it's a&nbsp;
convenient kind of notation for us all right.

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:52.560
Now let's introduce these counting&nbsp;
functions which tell us how big msets are,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:57.240
and there's different levels of&nbsp;
counting functions, sort of more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:03.000
sophisticated ones as we go on. So,&nbsp;
we're working always with pure msets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:09.900
I remind you. That's the framework where we start&nbsp;
with the empty msets and we only create msets by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:16.560
using empty msets and containments of&nbsp;
boxes and boxes. Okay, so there are no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:24.000
other external mathematical objects at this stage,&nbsp;
we just have empty boxes and we put those empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:29.100
boxes inside other boxes to form sort of nested&nbsp;
collections of boxes, so there's nothing else.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:38.220
Okay, so the first function, very simple, is that&nbsp;
if A is a pure mset, we define Z of A to be zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:45.300
the empty mset. So, every mset when you apply the&nbsp;
Zed counting function to it, you always get zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:53.400
It's pretty simple. N. So, N is defined this&nbsp;
way: if A is a pure set, then capital N of A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.400 --> 00:12:01.920
is the mset consisting of things that form&nbsp;
as Z of A as A runs through A. So, for each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:09.300
element of capital A, we take Z of that. In other&nbsp;
words, we're essentially replacing it with zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:13.620
So, we're looking inside A, oh there's all&nbsp;
these boxes, we're replacing each of those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.620 --> 00:12:18.360
boxes and all their contents with a single&nbsp;
zero, single zero, single zero, single zero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:25.020
The result then is naturally a natural number&nbsp;
because we're getting an mset of zeros. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:31.440
for example, if A is this same set here, then&nbsp;
Z of A, of course, is zero, and N of A, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:36.420
we have to apply Z to each of the elements.&nbsp;
So, is that a zero? Z is zero, Z of one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:41.880
and Z of the mset two, three. Well, each of these&nbsp;
is zero, so we get zero, zero, zero, zero, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:48.480
we recognize that's the natural number four. So,&nbsp;
this is how we are counting in sort of the naive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:58.620
basic fashion. The N function is doing that, it's&nbsp;
basically replacing elements with zeros. It might&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:03.900
be worthwhile to point out that this is in some&nbsp;
sense like almost a prehistoric kind of simple&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:13.020
kind of thing. It's analogous to some kids 100,000&nbsp;
years ago seeing some animals at a waterhole, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:13.020 --> 00:13:16.320
they want to convey how many animals there are,&nbsp;
and so they're going to go, there's an animal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:19.260
there's an animal, there's an animal, there's&nbsp;
an animal, there's that many animals. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:24.060
they walk home, they say, oh look, that's&nbsp;
how many animals there are at the waterhole.

00:13:25.140 --> 00:13:28.560
So, you don't really need a&nbsp;
prior language of numbers;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:28.560 --> 00:13:33.840
you just need some physical representation,&nbsp;
some simpler representation of the complicated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.040
set out there. Sort of what we're doing&nbsp;
here, the fingers are being represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:42.900
just by these zeros. These zeros here are just&nbsp;
representing these more complicated objects.

00:13:43.860 --> 00:13:48.120
Now, let's go to one level higher&nbsp;
and define the P counting function.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.900 --> 00:14:00.120
So, P of an mset A is the mset of N of A where A&nbsp;
is in capital A. So, each of the elements of A, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:00.780 --> 00:14:08.520
apply N to it, getting therefore a natural number,&nbsp;
and then we put all those natural numbers in an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:14.100
mset. So, obviously, what we're getting here&nbsp;
is a poly number, necessarily by definition.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:22.620
So, what we're doing now is we're assigning a more&nbsp;
sophisticated sort of object to this thing that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:29.220
we're counting that might be roughly analogous to&nbsp;
a more sophisticated child who goes and sees the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.220 --> 00:14:33.420
five animals at the water hole and says, "Aha!&nbsp;
But they're actually three antelope." Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:33.420 --> 00:14:38.100
it doesn't say three, he says, "There are this&nbsp;
many antelope, antelope, antelope, antelope," and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:43.920
"There are this many lions, lion, lion." Okay, and&nbsp;
he walks home like this and says, "Look, this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:50.400
what's at the water hole: antelopes, lions." Okay,&nbsp;
that's more information, that's more detailed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:54.900
information than just saying that there's this&nbsp;
many animals. That's sort of what we're doing.

00:14:55.680 --> 00:15:03.480
And then, next level, the multiset&nbsp;
analog M of A is the mset of P of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:10.560
little A's where A is in capital A. Okay,&nbsp;
let's do an example. So, here is an mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:21.720
B. So, there's an mset, there's an mset, there's&nbsp;
an mset. Okay, so Z of B, well, Z of B is always&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.720 --> 00:15:28.080
zero. N of B, we have to replace the elements&nbsp;
with zero. So, this element is replaced with zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.080 --> 00:15:31.380
this element is replaced with zero, this element&nbsp;
is replaced with zero. Again, zero, zero, zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:38.640
which is the number three. So, N of B is three.&nbsp;
What is P of B? Well, we have to take N of this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:44.100
we have to take N of this, we have to take N&nbsp;
of this, and we have to form an mset of those,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.100 --> 00:15:48.660
alright? So, what is N of this? Well, that&nbsp;
means we have to count what's inside here. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:54.600
what does that mean? It means that we have to&nbsp;
look inside this absent and apply Z to each of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:59.940
the elements. So, we have to apply Z to 2 and&nbsp;
we have to apply Z to 4. We're going to get 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.940 --> 00:16:10.586
0. So, N of this thing is the mset 0, 0, which is&nbsp;
the number two. Here, when you get the mset 0, 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.586 --> 00:16:15.960
0, which is the number three, here, we're going&nbsp;
to get the mset 0, 0, which is the number two.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:27.960
So, this thing, it's a poly number, it's an mset&nbsp;
of natural numbers, is the P of B, this mset B.

00:16:30.840 --> 00:16:36.660
It's a sort of more refined information,&nbsp;
right? The N of B is telling you, "Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:36.660 --> 00:16:40.680
this thing has three things in it," that's&nbsp;
what that's telling you. This thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

