Well, because, you know, here's an M set A, it has&nbsp;
various elements, and we're wedging it with mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:24.660 --> 00:33:27.780
one. So what does that mean we have to do? Well,&nbsp;
we have to perform all possible pairs between this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:32.220
one and these other guys, and we have to multiply&nbsp;
them. So we have to do one times this one times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:39.240
this one times this, etc. Well, the one is acting&nbsp;
as the identity in the multiplication level. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:48.600
um, and so this mset one is going to act as&nbsp;
the identity at the exponentiation level.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:53.880
See? And it's kind of beautiful.&nbsp;
You can kind of sort of see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:53.880 --> 00:33:58.800
these patterns are just going to keep on&nbsp;
extending, right? This is big arithmetic.

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:06.600
Okay, so we are going to talk more about&nbsp;
exponentiation because in fact it has a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:14.700
very important consequence in terms of rethinking&nbsp;
our framework for multinumbers. But what I want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:14.700 --> 00:34:19.680
to do before that is connect directly with&nbsp;
computer science. So probably a lot of you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:19.680 --> 00:34:26.580
will have figured this out already by now: that&nbsp;
this discussion of M sets nested in each other is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:35.160
really very close to a discussion of trees, which&nbsp;
we sort of refer to as rooted trees in computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:35.160 --> 00:34:41.220
science. And so I want to talk about that, and&nbsp;
I want to show you that in fact, in some sense,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:41.220 --> 00:34:45.840
this arithmetic has probably been under the&nbsp;
noses of the computer scientists for a long time.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:46.440 --> 00:34:50.880
In fact, I wouldn't at all be surprised if&nbsp;
some computer scientist somewhere or other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:55.980
had already developed this kind of thing. In&nbsp;
fact, it would be a little bit of a surprise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:55.980 --> 00:35:00.060
if that wasn't the case, to be honest. But in any&nbsp;
case, I think it'll be quite interesting because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:00.060 --> 00:35:07.260
it'll give us another kind of way of visualizing&nbsp;
what this arithmetic looks like. Hope you'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:11.880
join me for that. I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
Thanks for listening and happy New Year!

